00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:04.310
Because it covers your own introduction to
the sport.

00:02:04.310 --> 00:02:10.759
You were a highly competent experienced professional
broadcaster who was parachuted into the.

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:14.239
[Loud Siren Noise]
Ned, is that you?

00:02:14.239 --> 00:02:15.620
&gt;&gt;Ned: [slap] got it.

00:02:15.620 --> 00:02:18.540
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Richard: You were parachuted into the.

00:02:18.540 --> 00:02:22.060
[loud sirens stopped]
[laughter]

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:25.219
Tour de France in 2003.

00:02:25.219 --> 00:02:30.150
The title of the book comes from a pretty
embarrassing encounter you had on the Champs-Elysees

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:32.810
after the first stage of Prague time trial.

00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:33.969
Can you tell us?

00:02:33.969 --> 00:02:38.430
&gt;&gt;Ned: In very brief summary it was the first
bike race I'd ever seen of any description.

00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:42.219
I'd never ridden a bike, raced a bike, seen
a bike race.

00:02:42.219 --> 00:02:48.510
So my first introduction to it was the prologue
of the 2003 Tour de France which cycling fans

00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:52.609
here will remember, turns out to be one of
the most epic in modern times.

00:02:52.609 --> 00:02:58.189
The prologue was in Paris which is unusual
in itself, so the setting was extremely grand.

00:02:58.189 --> 00:03:00.540
Not only that, to compound the importance
of the occasion.

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:06.829
But a British rider David Miller pre-doping
ban was actually the hot favorite.

00:03:06.829 --> 00:03:07.840
&gt;&gt;: Daniel: Mid-doping.

00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:13.180
&gt;&gt;Ned: Mid-doping was for good reason the
hot favorite to win that day.

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:17.969
[laughter]
And so he should've done actually had it not

00:03:17.969 --> 00:03:23.510
been for the fact that in the final bend onto
the final home straight his chain bounced

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:28.950
off his chain ring and he lost time and just
missed out.

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:33.450
Anyway, this all sort of, we were broadcasting
live on ITV 1 actually then, not on ITV 4.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:37.090
So on the big network to a big audience.

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:41.010
And all this chaos ensued where we thought
we had this British winner and in the end

00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:45.400
he missed out by a fraction of the second,
rode over the line, disappeared and we had

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:48.590
to find out what had happened to him because
we couldn't get an interview with David Miller.

00:03:48.590 --> 00:03:54.109
And it's one of those broadcasting situations
where television is in desperate need for

00:03:54.109 --> 00:03:57.849
information to relay home but more often than
not you haven't got it.

00:03:57.849 --> 00:03:59.430
So you start kind of making stuff up.

00:03:59.430 --> 00:04:03.689
And the director without really warning me
just suddenly made the presenter Gary Imlach

00:04:03.689 --> 00:04:05.269
run out of things to say.

00:04:05.269 --> 00:04:08.120
Cause he had used up all the scanned information
he had.

00:04:08.120 --> 00:04:13.269
He kind of threw across to me to say what
I knew about the situation.

00:04:13.269 --> 00:04:17.739
And I was in a complete state of confusion,
so the only thing that came out of my mouth

00:04:17.739 --> 00:04:21.269
was, "David Miller's just blown his chances
of winning the yellow jumper."

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:28.680
Not realizing that of course it's not a jumper,
it's a jersey, it's an iconic sporting trophy

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:30.940
and I just made a bloody fool of myself.

00:04:30.940 --> 00:04:35.030
I didn't realize I'd done that until much
later when some people told me how much of

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:36.620
a tit I'd made out of myself.

00:04:36.620 --> 00:04:38.180
So that was it.

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:41.699
So that's, in terms of that book that's the
starting point.

00:04:41.699 --> 00:04:44.639
That's the ignorance in which I could only
improve my knowledge.

00:04:44.639 --> 00:04:45.639
&gt;&gt;Richard: Yeah.

00:04:45.639 --> 00:04:49.380
You'd worked in other sports, football most
notably before then.

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:51.800
You covered that whole tour.

00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:56.479
What was it about the tour that fascinated
you and what surprised you about it as well

00:04:56.479 --> 00:04:59.400
as you kind of got to know and love it?

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:03.380
&gt;&gt;Ned: Well I guess, firstly the scale of
the event.

00:05:03.380 --> 00:05:07.919
Because, Daniel you been on the Tour de France,
you've done it many times and I'm sure amongst

00:05:07.919 --> 00:05:09.320
our audience here.

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:13.599
And that bloke sitting over there on his own,
hello mate.

00:05:13.599 --> 00:05:17.060
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Where is that guy?
&gt;&gt;Ned: I don't know where he is, it doesn't

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:18.060
matter don't ask.

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:21.780
Anyway I'm sure amongst us all, we've all
been and seen the Tour de France.

00:05:21.780 --> 00:05:26.259
And it's only when you actually see it face
to face you realize quite the scale of the

00:05:26.259 --> 00:05:27.259
operation.

00:05:27.259 --> 00:05:31.210
So in terms of what I do, broadcasting for
a television network what's called the zone

00:05:31.210 --> 00:05:36.160
technique which is the TV compound area that
you guys occasionally are allowed access to,

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:37.160
you print journalist.

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:39.199
But you know.

00:05:39.199 --> 00:05:44.009
Just the size of that, the number of big TV
trucks and the amount of cabling and different

00:05:44.009 --> 00:05:47.130
countries represented there is comparable
only I think.

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:50.590
I mean its way bigger than a World Cup Final
in football which would be way bigger.

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:51.590
&gt;&gt;Richard: Really?

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:54.690
&gt;&gt;Ned: It's much bigger than a Champions League
final, probably the doubles the amount of

00:05:54.690 --> 00:05:55.690
trucks.

00:05:55.690 --> 00:06:01.970
I think it's comparable to just gonna maybe
US presidential race in terms of the.

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:03.250
&gt;&gt;Richard: Wow, that surprises me.

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:04.289
&gt;&gt;Ned: It's just staggering.

00:06:04.289 --> 00:06:08.069
So in terms of the television side, I just
went my God.

00:06:08.069 --> 00:06:11.509
German television turns up year after year,
apparently they're not interested in it anymore

00:06:11.509 --> 00:06:13.909
so they've kinda scaled back their presence.

00:06:13.909 --> 00:06:18.340
They had 85 television vehicles on the race
every year.

00:06:18.340 --> 00:06:21.280
I mean we don't we've got three.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:23.960
[laughter]
So the scale was just breathtaking.

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:27.270
Lance Armstrong of course in 2003 that was
his fifth win.

00:06:27.270 --> 00:06:31.219
So his stock was possibly never higher than
then.

00:06:31.219 --> 00:06:33.629
And the interest in him was vast.

00:06:33.629 --> 00:06:38.590
And everywhere he went he was just descended
upon by hundreds and hundreds of journalists.

00:06:38.590 --> 00:06:43.319
I mean it was as if David Beckham had signed
for Real Madrid every day of the week three

00:06:43.319 --> 00:06:44.319
times.

00:06:44.319 --> 00:06:47.479
You know, it was kind of, that blew me away.

00:06:47.479 --> 00:06:49.670
And then there's sort of a flipside of that.

00:06:49.670 --> 00:06:50.670
And it's perhaps contradictory.

00:06:50.670 --> 00:06:56.819
But the access I got to these riders having
worked in the very sanitized world of football

00:06:56.819 --> 00:06:59.860
where you can't get near the buggers.

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:03.620
Just amazed me that you could go and knock
on their door, find out which hotel room they

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:06.930
were sleeping him because they'd tell you
at the reception.

00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:07.930
What room?

00:07:07.930 --> 00:07:08.930
Oh well there's a list.

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:11.080
&gt;&gt;Richard: Well there's some curious things.

00:07:11.080 --> 00:07:12.080
&gt;&gt;Ned: Just nuts.

00:07:12.080 --> 00:07:16.849
So all that thrilled me and excited me
And over the years, the penny dropped that

00:07:16.849 --> 00:07:21.180
actually as a broadcast journalist and obviously
is a written journalist.

00:07:21.180 --> 00:07:26.379
Not only are you granted huge access to this
great occasion but you can actually drive

00:07:26.379 --> 00:07:29.430
the agenda and even determine the outcome
of the race.

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:35.090
When I think of the way we persecuted Michael
Rasmussen in 2007.

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:38.080
We ultimately were the motor that got him
booted off the race.

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:42.770
If we hadn't been doing our job in the way
that we did it, someone else would've won.

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:44.069
And so that doesn't happen in football.

00:07:44.069 --> 00:07:46.129
You can't step on the pitch and get involved.

00:07:46.129 --> 00:07:48.210
But in cycling, you kind of can.

00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:50.360
&gt;&gt;Richard: The lines are far more blurred
aren't they?

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:51.360
&gt;&gt;Ned: The lines are blurred, it's fascinating.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:56.219
&gt;&gt;Richard: And there is that paradoxical element
to the scale on one hand and the access on

00:07:56.219 --> 00:07:57.219
the other.

00:07:57.219 --> 00:08:00.810
And one of the things that comes out in your
book is your relationships with the riders

00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:02.229
as they develop.

00:08:02.229 --> 00:08:03.469
&gt;&gt;Ned: Or not, yeah.

00:08:03.469 --> 00:08:04.469
&gt;&gt;Richard: Or not.

00:08:04.469 --> 00:08:05.469
Or appear to develop and then.

00:08:05.469 --> 00:08:10.360
I mean it's very much like your story of your
dealings with Mark Cavendish for example.

00:08:10.360 --> 00:08:11.680
It's like a courtship.

00:08:11.680 --> 00:08:12.680
You know where we.

00:08:12.680 --> 00:08:14.510
&gt;&gt;Ned: It's quite one sided.

00:08:14.510 --> 00:08:16.189
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Richard: Unrequited love.

00:08:16.189 --> 00:08:17.189
&gt;&gt;Ned: Yeah, yeah.

00:08:17.189 --> 00:08:19.970
&gt;&gt;Richard: But you feel it-
&gt;&gt;Ned: I've got a huge crush on him.

00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:20.970
&gt;&gt;Richard: On occasions yeah.

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:27.229
But it's fascinating how, and it's a very
interesting kind of study of how journalists

00:08:27.229 --> 00:08:28.760
interact with those athletes.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:32.500
I think you probably got some thoughts on
that as well Daniel cause you obviously.

00:08:32.500 --> 00:08:37.400
For those of us who don't know, Daniel is
Mark Cavendish's ghost so to speak.

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:41.580
&gt;&gt;Ned: "Boy Racer", Mark Cavendish's book
was actually written by this fella.

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:42.580
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I collaborated.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:45.170
I dotted a few "i's"
&gt;&gt;Ned: "Boy Racer", was written by.

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:48.381
&gt;&gt;Richard: He sorted out the grammar and the
spelling and stuff.

00:08:48.381 --> 00:08:50.520
[laughter]
But yeah, you know Mark very well.

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:54.100
But what comes across in the book is your
crush on Cavendish.

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:57.690
[laughter]
And there is this kind of, and then it's followed

00:08:57.690 --> 00:09:02.310
up in your follow-up book, a mini book which
is called "How Cam Won the Green Jersey."

00:09:02.310 --> 00:09:05.850
Which was an e-book published last year.

00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:10.080
You know, so it's a fascinating, like can
you tell us a little bit about how you and

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:11.080
Mark?

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:14.390
&gt;&gt;Ned: Well no let me just, very briefly I'd
like to you know come to you in a second.

00:09:14.390 --> 00:09:17.400
But I, I have repeatedly,
Mark and I have this game where I ask him

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:20.140
for his mobile phone number and he says no.

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:22.150
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I've got it actually.

00:09:22.150 --> 00:09:24.592
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Ned: Well that's the interesting thing,

00:09:24.592 --> 00:09:27.420
so I've, I mean every time I've seen him I've
gone, "Can I have your mobile phone number?"

00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:28.810
And he goes "No."

00:09:28.810 --> 00:09:30.910
And then I'll say, "Well I'll it again in
20 minutes, see what you say."

00:09:30.910 --> 00:09:33.200
So I, "Can I have your mobile phone number",
he'll go, "No you can't."

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:34.200
This goes on and on.

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:36.560
&gt;&gt;Richard: But things seem to be going very
well for you at certain points.

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:39.400
&gt;&gt;Ned: Yeah, but that's a funny thing about
Mark, he does kind of.

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:40.490
&gt;&gt;Richard: Lead you on.

00:09:40.490 --> 00:09:41.490
&gt;&gt;Ned: Blow hot and cold.

00:09:41.490 --> 00:09:44.720
And you know, he never gives you anything
other than compelling television I think,

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:45.720
whether he's.

00:09:45.720 --> 00:09:48.590
In fact he's at his most compelling when he's
got a right ass with you.

00:09:48.590 --> 00:09:49.820
Because that's when you see the true.

00:09:49.820 --> 00:09:51.680
You know it makes my job slightly uncomfortable.

00:09:51.680 --> 00:09:55.760
But I'm not there to be his mate, I'm there
to kind of be the lightning conductor and

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:59.150
the filter through which we experience what
he is as a person.

00:09:59.150 --> 00:10:00.150
What drives him.

00:10:00.150 --> 00:10:02.950
And I think that across most when he's got
the ass with you, which is quite often.

00:10:02.950 --> 00:10:04.810
&gt;&gt;Richard: how uncomfortable are those moments?

00:10:04.810 --> 00:10:05.810
&gt;&gt;Ned: Oh, hideously.

00:10:05.810 --> 00:10:07.150
It sucks the air out of the room.

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:11.220
I mean it's just, when Mark doesn't want.

00:10:11.220 --> 00:10:12.580
You know I'm interested in your take on this.

00:10:12.580 --> 00:10:17.640
When Mark doesn't want to cooperate or when
he thinks you are letting yourself down or

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:21.700
not paying him enough respect or failing to
understand him or just being daft which is

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:22.700
quite often.

00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:25.800
He just has a way of shutting down the communication,
doesn't he?

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:27.720
It's quite unique.

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:30.900
I mean did you find that, even when you're
you know, when you're writing the book with

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:31.900
them?

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:32.900
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I think he's very fickle.

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:33.940
He tends to make up his mind about people.

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:35.950
And, he's obviously made up his mind about
you.

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:40.100
[laughter]
If he likes you he tends to be fine.

00:10:40.100 --> 00:10:45.400
I mean I remember about a year or two ago
you know I'd done the whole book with him

00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:46.850
and we got on pretty well.

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:50.580
I wouldn't call us friends, but we had a good
professional relationship.

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:52.520
And I had to do a magazine feature.

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:55.530
And I called him up and asked him to couple
questions.

00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:57.220
And I asked him one question, I think it was
about a race.

00:10:57.220 --> 00:11:00.250
Milan-San Remo last year or the year before.

00:11:00.250 --> 00:11:03.220
And there was a pause on the end the phone.

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:04.220
It was a phone interview.

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:08.240
He said, "Daniel, I don't think I've said
this to you before, that was fucking stupid

00:11:08.240 --> 00:11:09.240
question."

00:11:09.240 --> 00:11:13.220
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Daniel: And I mean that's kind a typical

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:17.490
of him, like you say even when he's pissed
off it can be very compelling.

00:11:17.490 --> 00:11:20.850
&gt;&gt;Ned: Incidentally I've got his mobile phone
number now because another journalist gave

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:23.270
it to me and said by the way here.

00:11:23.270 --> 00:11:24.270
But I've never used it.

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:27.600
I'm far too proud to use it now it, because
it hasn't come from him so I'm not gonna use

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:28.600
it.

00:11:28.600 --> 00:11:30.290
But, I'll sell it to anyone in this room for
about a tenner.

00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:32.430
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Richard: Or anyone in the googlesphere.

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:35.640
&gt;&gt;Daniel: That's just us then.

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:38.320
&gt;&gt;Ned: The other guys disappeared.

00:11:38.320 --> 00:11:41.770
&gt;&gt;Richard: But, you know that's one very interesting
aspect.

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:46.490
And these characters are kind of a big part
of the story that you tell in the book it.

00:11:46.490 --> 00:11:48.360
Lance Armstrong being another one.

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:52.100
I mean you've obviously covered lots of major
sports, how does Lance Armstrong compare to

00:11:52.100 --> 00:11:57.000
some of the kind of A-listers in football
for example?

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.280
&gt;&gt;Ned: Armstrong's in the same way that Cavendish
is a bundle of contradictions, so too is Armstrong.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:04.680
But I mean Armstrong, I've lost interest in
him a bit now.

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:05.680
But that's only quite recently.

00:12:05.680 --> 00:12:09.520
I mean I found him absolutely compelling in
all sorts of different ways.

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:13.860
Because he, you know I found tussling with
him on the finish line a different kind of

00:12:13.860 --> 00:12:14.860
experience.

00:12:14.860 --> 00:12:17.310
Cause he was quite even-tempered.

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:22.570
But he had this way of fixing you with a little
glare.

00:12:22.570 --> 00:12:25.200
And lying through his teeth to you like that.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:29.030
And you kind of knew it was a lie and he knew
that you knew it was a lie.

00:12:29.030 --> 00:12:31.980
But we were playing this game and it sort
of dancing around that.

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:33.580
But it was such fun with him.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:39.270
I did, for all we think of his record as an
athlete, good and bad, he was compelling I

00:12:39.270 --> 00:12:42.070
think to watch in all situations.

00:12:42.070 --> 00:12:47.520
&gt;&gt;Richard: Shall we kind of segue very smoothly
from talking about Armstrong to talking about

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:52.420
the rider to whom Armstrong was perhaps--
&gt;&gt;Ned: Lifetime champion, yeah.

00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:53.620
&gt;&gt;Richard: compared the most.

00:12:53.620 --> 00:12:57.280
"The Cannibal", Eddy Merckx, the greatest
cyclist of them all.

00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:02.570
Who quite strangely enough for Merckx and
Armstrong were kind of rivals through history

00:13:02.570 --> 00:13:03.570
in a sense.

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:08.880
Merckx is generally acknowledged as the greatest
cyclist of all time, and Armstrong though

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:13.350
during his reign was regularly kind of mentioned
as perhaps the greatest cyclist of all time.

00:13:13.350 --> 00:13:17.500
Can you maybe just tell us a little bit about
your approach to this book?

00:13:17.500 --> 00:13:21.640
Because Merckx didn't cooperate as such with
you did he?

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:26.530
&gt;&gt;Daniel: No he told me pretty much from the
outset that he wouldn't collaborate.

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:27.900
I don't think that's that unusual with biographies.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:31.330
I think, and it kind of freed me up really.

00:13:31.330 --> 00:13:38.530
I didn't, he's one of these people, he's really
dehumanized and demystified himself over the

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:41.200
last 30 or 40 years since he's been retired.

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:46.810
Kind of disappointingly, like Pele you know
with his Viagra adverts and you know the nonsense.

00:13:46.810 --> 00:13:47.810
&gt;&gt;Ned: MasterCard.

00:13:47.810 --> 00:13:50.830
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Yeah, MasterCard and the nonsense
he talks about the current Brazilian footballers.

00:13:50.830 --> 00:13:54.700
So Merckx is quite a disappointing character.

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:58.600
But when you juxtapose that with his achievements
which are just extraordinary and the person

00:13:58.600 --> 00:14:02.160
he turned into when he was on a bike, that
in itself was fascinating.

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:04.590
But it was really that that I wanted to concentrate
on.

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:10.510
Because, we're not that interested in, I mean,
it goes back to what you are saying about

00:14:10.510 --> 00:14:12.580
your interactions with these guys.

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:16.060
We're not that interested in them as human
beings, we're interested in them because they

00:14:16.060 --> 00:14:17.680
can do things that we can't.

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:21.130
And that was very much the case with Merckx.

00:14:21.130 --> 00:14:26.460
And another thing that I really wanted to
tell was the story of all the people's lives,

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:27.460
careers he ruined.

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:30.170
I mean he sounds like a despot and he kind
of was on a bike.

00:14:30.170 --> 00:14:35.350
And there was this whole generation of guys
who could and probably thought when they were

00:14:35.350 --> 00:14:41.820
19, 20, 21 that they were gonna be you know
Mohammed Ali on a bike, or Pele on a bike.

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:43.190
And that didn't happen.

00:14:43.190 --> 00:14:47.330
And it was interesting really looking at how
that shaped them as characters.

00:14:47.330 --> 00:14:50.590
It actually made the more complete characters
than Merckx.

00:14:50.590 --> 00:14:55.780
And Merckx sort of remained this kind of Peter
Pan never grew up, because you know losing

00:14:55.780 --> 00:14:58.090
is an inexperience, we all have setbacks in
our lives.

00:14:58.090 --> 00:15:01.110
But Merckx managed to keep a lid on everything.

00:15:01.110 --> 00:15:08.560
And kind of remain in his own mind immortal,
invulnerable until the age of about 32, 33

00:15:08.560 --> 00:15:10.450
when he finally lost for the first time.

00:15:10.450 --> 00:15:13.740
And then couldn't deal with it, he found it
very, very difficult to deal with.

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:19.110
&gt;&gt;Ned: Can I just ask Daniel, I mean having
to learn about cycling history in the way

00:15:19.110 --> 00:15:21.631
that I have to because I didn't watch it first
time around.

00:15:21.631 --> 00:15:23.700
And anyway, Merckx was before my time.

00:15:23.700 --> 00:15:28.940
But what I really got from your book was a
sense of a rider who could do it on all terrains.

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:32.920
And that's kind of remarkable in the modern
era to think back to a rider who did that.

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:35.140
So he could time trial like no other.

00:15:35.140 --> 00:15:37.270
He could win rolling intermediate stages.

00:15:37.270 --> 00:15:41.780
He won in the high mountains and he could
win up on sprint.

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:47.070
If you chucked Eddy Merckx on to a carbon
fiber bike and stuck him in a modern peloton,

00:15:47.070 --> 00:15:49.230
where would you find his, what would he do?

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:50.230
What would he achieve?

00:15:50.230 --> 00:15:52.530
And where would that take him?

00:15:52.530 --> 00:15:54.440
&gt;&gt;Daniel: It's a good question.

00:15:54.440 --> 00:15:58.320
I actually just wrote a magazine feature about
this.

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:03.790
I think the way cycling has gone, it's become
so specialized, kind of disappointingly so.

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:09.840
To the extent where a guy now will literally
dedicate six months if not a year to one race.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:12.120
And he will be thinking about that race the
whole time.

00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:15.650
He'll be developing his bike with a view to
that race.

00:16:15.650 --> 00:16:18.900
He'll be getting coaching with a view to that
race.

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:20.690
And that really wasn't the case.

00:16:20.690 --> 00:16:27.290
And that kind of falsifies Merckx's achievements
when you compare them to achievements nowadays.

00:16:27.290 --> 00:16:32.770
Is he probably wasn't as good pound for pound
in the Tour de France as you know whoever

00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:34.520
wins it this year would be.

00:16:34.520 --> 00:16:35.520
He would lose.

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:38.160
Because he was never as fit I don't think
as the guys are now.

00:16:38.160 --> 00:16:42.200
But he, he was good enough throughout the
years to beat those guys cause they didn't

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:43.200
have access to those things.

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:46.410
&gt;&gt;Ned: So the modern sport would force him
if you like to specialize, to choose one of

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:47.410
those routes.

00:16:47.410 --> 00:16:48.610
And what would be that route do you think?

00:16:48.610 --> 00:16:50.930
What was his single greatest strength?

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:52.990
Was it – –
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I mean I think.

00:16:52.990 --> 00:16:54.920
&gt;&gt;Ned: Would he be [Migar Linderhine]?

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:57.090
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I think he would be a one-day racer.

00:16:57.090 --> 00:17:02.950
I mean he's a fairly big guy, six-foot and
weighs 75 kg.

00:17:02.950 --> 00:17:06.799
I would imagine that he would concentrate
on the classics, the one-day races in springtime.

00:17:06.799 --> 00:17:10.350
&gt;&gt;Richard: He'd be a far more limited rider
then wouldn't he?

00:17:10.350 --> 00:17:13.680
And he probably wouldn't have the respect
that is his due?

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:16.089
I mean he's not.

00:17:16.089 --> 00:17:19.250
Because you couldn't imagine him really going
head-to-head with some of the great climbers.

00:17:19.250 --> 00:17:23.970
Why were those great climbers not able to
put him on the ropes back in the day?

00:17:23.970 --> 00:17:26.300
&gt;&gt;Daniel: It's not were.

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:30.650
But again I think there's another aspect of
it was this aura.

00:17:30.650 --> 00:17:36.650
And he, particularly the first year when he
won the Tour de France in 1969, he really

00:17:36.650 --> 00:17:37.650
traumatized people.

00:17:37.650 --> 00:17:42.700
There was actually a quote from a guy, one
of his old team managers in my book saying,

00:17:42.700 --> 00:17:44.640
he actually, you know, they were shell-shocked.

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:47.780
Not just for a few weeks, but for years afterwards.

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:51.340
And one of the things he said to me was, "They
would never, they would not dare to attack

00:17:51.340 --> 00:17:54.300
because it was like literally dangling bait
in front of him."

00:17:54.300 --> 00:17:57.930
And as soon as you attack, that was literally
like lighting.

00:17:57.930 --> 00:18:01.230
&gt;&gt;Richard: Tell us the great story about the
wine.

00:18:01.230 --> 00:18:04.480
Zandegù and the wine.

00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:05.480
&gt;&gt;Ned: Yeah.

00:18:05.480 --> 00:18:12.641
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I remember the tour with him, [inaudible]
&gt;&gt;Daniel: No I mean you know races, the Tour

00:18:12.641 --> 00:18:16.480
de France, now you get the hotspot sprints
for points for the green jersey.

00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:21.400
Whereas it used to be very common for the
spot prices to be up for grabs, like bottles

00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:22.470
of wine.

00:18:22.470 --> 00:18:27.220
On this particular case in the Tour of Italy,
they went past this famous Italian singer's

00:18:27.220 --> 00:18:32.340
Château kind of castle manor house that he
had.

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:36.510
And he was putting up 50 bottles of Chianti
for the winner of this sprint.

00:18:36.510 --> 00:18:42.080
And this Italian rider Dino Zandegù who became
a bit of a folk hero because he was just,

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:43.320
he was a circus act.

00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:49.340
You know he would, appear holding birthday
cakes in the middle of the race and singing

00:18:49.340 --> 00:18:50.420
"Happy birthday."

00:18:50.420 --> 00:18:53.400
[laughter]
So this one day he resolved that he was gonna

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:54.400
win this Chianti.

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:58.570
He said whenever there was wine up for grab,
and this is something that I kind of picked

00:18:58.570 --> 00:18:59.570
up when I interviewed him.

00:18:59.570 --> 00:19:04.070
Because you could kind of tell he was fond
of a glass of Chianti or two

00:19:04.070 --> 00:19:06.760
&gt;&gt;Richard: He got drunk during the course
of the day, didn't he?

00:19:06.760 --> 00:19:10.100
&gt;&gt;Daniel: But he was particularly motivated
for this kind of sprint.

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:13.360
So on this one day, he described it in perfect
detail.

00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:16.950
You know coming around a bridge and there
it was the banner.

00:19:16.950 --> 00:19:18.560
And he could see it, and off he went.

00:19:18.560 --> 00:19:22.850
And he was a sprinter anyway, so on this particular
he managed to beat Merckx.

00:19:22.850 --> 00:19:24.850
Completely meaningless, Merckx was gonna win
the race.

00:19:24.850 --> 00:19:28.150
He was minutes ahead on the general classification.

00:19:28.150 --> 00:19:32.770
And when he saw Zandegù cross the line, he
was screaming at you, "You bastardo, you'll

00:19:32.770 --> 00:19:33.970
never race again."

00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:38.710
Or "I'm gonna kill you", and, "That Chianti's
mine."

00:19:38.710 --> 00:19:44.940
Anyway that night, they were all staying in
the same hotel, all the teams up on Copper

00:19:44.940 --> 00:19:45.940
Mountain.

00:19:45.940 --> 00:19:50.720
And Merckx knocked on his door and demanding
half of the Chianti otherwise he was gonna

00:19:50.720 --> 00:19:53.820
see to it that this guy never race again.

00:19:53.820 --> 00:19:57.930
That's kind of, I'm sure there's a degree
of truth in that.

00:19:57.930 --> 00:20:00.360
But I'm not sure –
&gt;&gt;Richard: The other day he beat Merckx again

00:20:00.360 --> 00:20:01.980
and had to hide in somebody's house.

00:20:01.980 --> 00:20:06.020
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Beat Merckx again and he pulled
off the road just after the finish line, and

00:20:06.020 --> 00:20:11.560
he burst into this little wooden shack near
the finish line to a completely deserted house

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:12.820
and he went upstairs.

00:20:12.820 --> 00:20:16.270
And there was an eighty-year-old woman asleep,
and she started screaming.

00:20:16.270 --> 00:20:20.750
He said "Granny, granny don't worry, I'm not
gonna do anything to you, but Eddy Merckx

00:20:20.750 --> 00:20:22.220
is chasing me and he wants to rip my head
and face off."

00:20:22.220 --> 00:20:27.520
[laughter]
He actually saved it now, I mean I didn't

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:28.830
believe a word of it.

00:20:28.830 --> 00:20:31.420
[laughter]
But hope I present it in the book in such

00:20:31.420 --> 00:20:32.420
a way that.

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:36.110
&gt;&gt;Richard: You get a sense that Zandegù is
a circus act.

00:20:36.110 --> 00:20:40.980
It's interesting because paradoxically Merckx,
you know the way you describe him there he's

00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:43.260
sort of a mafia boss or a bully.

00:20:43.260 --> 00:20:46.390
And yet he's quite gentle guy as well.

00:20:46.390 --> 00:20:50.280
He's got this, and he's racked by the insecurity
and doubt himself.

00:20:50.280 --> 00:20:57.270
You know, which in contrast to this marauding
bullying bike rider and racer that he was.

00:20:57.270 --> 00:20:59.490
&gt;&gt;Ned: That's no different from lots of bike
riders is it?

00:20:59.490 --> 00:21:00.490
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Same with Cavendish.

00:21:00.490 --> 00:21:02.570
&gt;&gt;Ned: There's a life on the bike and there's
a life off the bike.

00:21:02.570 --> 00:21:05.710
&gt;&gt;Richard: Apart from Lance Armstrong who
kind of had that.

00:21:05.710 --> 00:21:08.840
&gt;&gt;Ned: took his on bike persona and turned
it into his off bike.

00:21:08.840 --> 00:21:13.190
&gt;&gt;Richard: And you know Armstrong was probably
well you know and then Armstrong was the next

00:21:13.190 --> 00:21:14.190
guy.

00:21:14.190 --> 00:21:18.520
[Inaudible]
&gt;&gt;Richard: That was completely accidental,

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:19.660
that was totally accidental.

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:21.430
&gt;&gt;Ned: Should we ask him about that?

00:21:21.430 --> 00:21:22.950
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Let's ask him about that.

00:21:22.950 --> 00:21:24.460
&gt;&gt;Richard: Oh goodness, if you must.

00:21:24.460 --> 00:21:26.480
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Daniel: So you've written a book called

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:27.480
"Slaying the Badger."

00:21:27.480 --> 00:21:28.760
Now "the badger" is Bernard Hinault.

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:32.870
Which you want to explain first of all how
he got this nickname and why it's appropriate?

00:21:32.870 --> 00:21:37.270
&gt;&gt;Richard: I don't think the reason why he
got the nickname owes to the person he became

00:21:37.270 --> 00:21:38.270
in a way.

00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:45.600
It's kind of odd, the origins of it were apparently
when he was a young cyclist, a teammate from

00:21:45.600 --> 00:21:48.370
Brittany used to greet him "Hey badger, hey
blairo."

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:50.372
&gt;&gt;Daniel: It's quite common in France isn't
it?

00:21:50.372 --> 00:21:55.710
&gt;&gt;Richard: Apparently in Brittany it's a common
form of greeting, "Hey badger.

00:21:55.710 --> 00:21:58.190
" [chuckles] So with Hinault this kind of
stuck.

00:21:58.190 --> 00:22:03.900
And then I think I had this image of a badger
as this cuddly kind of toy.

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:06.500
And a badger is really pretty vicious apparently.

00:22:06.500 --> 00:22:13.820
And the jaw kind of, once it clamps, you can
only get it off by dislocating the jaw apparently.

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:18.370
And that sums up Hinault to a T. He grew into
that nickname, and it caught on.

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:25.951
And you know, when, when I went with a good
friend/translator of mine and Daniel to interview

00:22:25.951 --> 00:22:26.951
him.

00:22:26.951 --> 00:22:30.300
You know we asked him, he quite liked it,
didn't he?

00:22:30.300 --> 00:22:31.940
And he goes, "Yeah."

00:22:31.940 --> 00:22:33.780
And I think it kind of suited him.

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:36.100
He said, "Badgers a little bit nasty like
me."

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:39.590
So it does kind of sum him up, yeah.

00:22:39.590 --> 00:22:42.200
&gt;&gt;Ned: In terms of what happened on a bike,
sorry Daniel.

00:22:42.200 --> 00:22:46.440
When I read your book a while ago, when I
had been reading Daniels.

00:22:46.440 --> 00:22:53.200
The way in the general classification Merckx
would make decisive moves that would nowadays

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:55.390
in the modern era be considered suicidal.

00:22:55.390 --> 00:22:59.120
Cause they just go off with 100 km to go on
their own and just kind of wing it.

00:22:59.120 --> 00:23:00.290
"Let's get this done, let's just do it."

00:23:00.290 --> 00:23:01.690
Hinault was the same right?

00:23:01.690 --> 00:23:04.470
I mean repeatedly that would be his modus
operandi.

00:23:04.470 --> 00:23:07.380
&gt;&gt;Richard: To a point, in the early part of
his career certainly.

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:11.781
And it's interesting cause Hinault retired,
I'm sorry, Merckx retired in 78', the year

00:23:11.781 --> 00:23:14.250
that Hinault won his first Tour de France.

00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:19.740
And I think Anquetil retired the year that
Merckx also won his first tour.

00:23:19.740 --> 00:23:23.230
Or there was some neat cut off between these
eras.

00:23:23.230 --> 00:23:29.270
And there was the Anquetil era, followed by
the Merckx era followed almost directly afterward

00:23:29.270 --> 00:23:31.200
by the Hinault era.

00:23:31.200 --> 00:23:37.891
And Hinault was, he was so physically capable
I think that early on in his career, you know

00:23:37.891 --> 00:23:42.470
he realized he could win big races and he
was quite aggressive.

00:23:42.470 --> 00:23:44.770
He suffered a bad knee injury in 1980.

00:23:44.770 --> 00:23:48.850
And it caused him to withdraw from the tour
midway through when he was wearing the yellow

00:23:48.850 --> 00:23:50.010
jersey.

00:23:50.010 --> 00:23:55.750
And in the dead of night, after the Germans
had done their stories for the next day Hinault

00:23:55.750 --> 00:23:59.890
orchestrated this exit which didn't go down
very well for journalists.

00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:05.000
And after that, he was a slightly different
kind of rider.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:09.559
He did go to the world championship that year
and won it in that style, that buccaneering.

00:24:09.559 --> 00:24:12.460
But he was more calculating afterwards.

00:24:12.460 --> 00:24:19.780
And that calculation extended to individual
races but also to his career.

00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:22.360
He became far more selective.

00:24:22.360 --> 00:24:26.400
Not quite as selective as Lance Armstrong
who only went to the tour to win each year.

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:29.360
But far more selective than Merckx had been.

00:24:29.360 --> 00:24:32.900
You know he set his sights on, he had appointments.

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:36.809
And when he turned up for an appointment he
won it every time.

00:24:36.809 --> 00:24:40.309
He would say, "I'm gonna win that race", and
he would go and win it.

00:24:40.309 --> 00:24:45.170
And at other races he would sort of become
this incredible teammate to his, to lesser

00:24:45.170 --> 00:24:49.380
riders who he would help and act as this incredible
domestique.

00:24:49.380 --> 00:24:56.180
And speaking to his former teammates, they
were, they spoke so kind of warmly even lovingly

00:24:56.180 --> 00:24:57.180
of him.

00:24:57.180 --> 00:25:01.900
