00:37:38.760 --> 00:37:59.559
&gt;&gt;male 6: [Inaudible]
Recently it hasn't really got my interest.

00:37:59.559 --> 00:38:09.559
I think it's because I thought everybody was
using drugs or doping.

00:38:09.559 --> 00:38:17.170
So my question to you is [Inaudible] because
right now I feel after 6 months [Inaudible]

00:38:17.170 --> 00:38:23.229
&gt;&gt;Ned: That's a big one.

00:38:23.229 --> 00:38:27.799
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I mean, there's no doubt that drugs
have been in cycling from the start pretty

00:38:27.799 --> 00:38:28.799
much.

00:38:28.799 --> 00:38:33.569
I mean strychnine, caffeine from the start.

00:38:33.569 --> 00:38:34.799
&gt;&gt;Richard: Morphine, alcohol.

00:38:34.799 --> 00:38:36.859
&gt;&gt;Ned: There's various different kinds.

00:38:36.859 --> 00:38:37.859
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Yeah.

00:38:37.859 --> 00:38:42.599
And I mean one misconception, one of the things
I talk about in my book is that it used to

00:38:42.599 --> 00:38:43.599
be.

00:38:43.599 --> 00:38:48.849
Now they refer to it as light doping i.e.
like stimulants and caffeine whereas now it's

00:38:48.849 --> 00:38:49.849
heavy doping.

00:38:49.849 --> 00:38:54.099
Because I think people of made a leap in their
minds because now it's syringes, and it kind

00:38:54.099 --> 00:38:56.099
of seems slightly sordid.

00:38:56.099 --> 00:38:58.660
Blood bags you know and shadowy doctors.

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:02.630
Whereas back then, it was, it seemed quite
innocent in a way.

00:39:02.630 --> 00:39:04.410
But it's always been there.

00:39:04.410 --> 00:39:07.940
And that is a misconception, you know a lot
of the methods and products that were around

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:10.290
now were around 30, 40 years ago.

00:39:10.290 --> 00:39:17.940
It's just that, we've stigmatized in a way
by making the punishments more draconian.

00:39:17.940 --> 00:39:21.869
You know we say now its two years, four years
and all of the sudden in people's minds "God

00:39:21.869 --> 00:39:23.220
this is a really terrible crime."

00:39:23.220 --> 00:39:28.869
Whereas if you say you're banned for a week,
then people start to view it as something

00:39:28.869 --> 00:39:29.869
that's kind of trifling.

00:39:29.869 --> 00:39:31.279
&gt;&gt;Ned: Eddy Mokes got a month right?

00:39:31.279 --> 00:39:35.140
&gt;&gt;Daniel: And then it was, yeah he didn't
even get the month.

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:38.390
So that's one of the things.

00:39:38.390 --> 00:39:42.880
&gt;&gt;Ned: Yeah, I would suggest that, even in
the 10 years I've been covering it actually.

00:39:42.880 --> 00:39:46.249
And I understand entirely what you're saying,
you're right to feel that in some ways.

00:39:46.249 --> 00:39:52.380
But I would suggest hesitantly that actually
incrementally over those 10 years the instances

00:39:52.380 --> 00:39:55.619
of doping have come down, year on year.

00:39:55.619 --> 00:39:59.680
And even those instances where people have
doped, I think probably the percentage of

00:39:59.680 --> 00:40:02.650
advantage they're gaining is probably smaller.

00:40:02.650 --> 00:40:07.940
In other words, the conclusion I'm trying
to draw is that it's getting better.

00:40:07.940 --> 00:40:09.309
And so what you do?

00:40:09.309 --> 00:40:12.890
Is this a point to give up on it?

00:40:12.890 --> 00:40:13.890
I'm not sure it is.

00:40:13.890 --> 00:40:17.470
I think that probably they, it's heading in
the right direction albeit slowly.

00:40:17.470 --> 00:40:21.660
&gt;&gt;Richard: I'm recently comforted in that
clean the riders are winning big races now

00:40:21.660 --> 00:40:23.720
in a way that it wasn't 10 years ago.

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:24.720
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Yeah.

00:40:24.720 --> 00:40:26.739
&gt;&gt;Richard: When I say clean, it's all relative.

00:40:26.739 --> 00:40:29.170
I mean we have this.

00:40:29.170 --> 00:40:33.769
Well I'm not casting aspersions here at all.

00:40:33.769 --> 00:40:37.420
You know we have this very black and white
viewpoint of doping that you're either a drug

00:40:37.420 --> 00:40:38.489
cheat or you're not.

00:40:38.489 --> 00:40:43.799
And it's just so complex you know there's
this huge gray area, and the actual line between

00:40:43.799 --> 00:40:46.869
doping and clean is moving all the time.

00:40:46.869 --> 00:40:50.390
You know that's something I covered in another
book about Team Sky where you know it was

00:40:50.390 --> 00:40:54.859
very obvious that if you’re a professional
athlete, if you're training for the Tour de

00:40:54.859 --> 00:40:57.930
France it's your job to go it's close to that
line is possible.

00:40:57.930 --> 00:41:01.499
And to do everything that you can that is
legal.

00:41:01.499 --> 00:41:05.250
Which might not be considered natural or even
ethical, I don't know.

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:06.250
And by some people.

00:41:06.250 --> 00:41:11.009
Athletes at that level are doing things and
taking things that the rest of us would regard

00:41:11.009 --> 00:41:13.720
as crazy.

00:41:13.720 --> 00:41:15.329
But it's kind of the responsibility to do
that.

00:41:15.329 --> 00:41:18.229
They would be kind of silly not to I think.

00:41:18.229 --> 00:41:19.690
In a way.

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:22.999
So I think it's a very foggy area.

00:41:22.999 --> 00:41:27.960
And there isn't this kind of, an athlete doesn't
decide alright I'm gonna dope today, I'm gonna

00:41:27.960 --> 00:41:29.420
go from being a clean rider to a cheat.

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:35.029
I think as David Miller very eloquently described
in his book, it's a process.

00:41:35.029 --> 00:41:39.300
But, there's always this puzzle.

00:41:39.300 --> 00:41:42.990
This game of being as close to that line as
you can possibly be.

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:46.720
&gt;&gt;Daniel: The other thing I'd say is that
there's this misconception that the media

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:48.150
knows.

00:41:48.150 --> 00:41:51.759
It's a charge that's often leveled at us that
we spent time with these athletes.

00:41:51.759 --> 00:41:54.390
We do have really good access like Ned said
earlier.

00:41:54.390 --> 00:41:56.130
We don't know, we have no idea.

00:41:56.130 --> 00:41:58.609
And the athletes themselves have no idea what
another guy.

00:41:58.609 --> 00:42:00.050
I mean in some cases they might.

00:42:00.050 --> 00:42:06.670
You know, at the Tour de France, the pressroom
is, you will not ever walked into a more cynicism

00:42:06.670 --> 00:42:09.869
fueled room.

00:42:09.869 --> 00:42:16.559
You know we watch the stage on the big screen
and you know as soon as anyone does something

00:42:16.559 --> 00:42:18.400
incredible they'll be a nudge, nudge and a
wink, wink.

00:42:18.400 --> 00:42:19.589
But really we don't know.

00:42:19.589 --> 00:42:20.589
&gt;&gt;Ned: Rumors.

00:42:20.589 --> 00:42:23.880
&gt;&gt;Daniel: And often we're basing that on stereotypes.

00:42:23.880 --> 00:42:27.599
&gt;&gt;Ned: And sometimes you'll be live to a,
I mean I don't dwell on it.

00:42:27.599 --> 00:42:31.460
You will be live to a decent rumor that you
can follow through and actually affect the

00:42:31.460 --> 00:42:32.460
challenge.

00:42:32.460 --> 00:42:33.880
I mean that does happen.

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:38.119
It happened with me and Stephan Schumacher
after his time trial win where I basically

00:42:38.119 --> 00:42:39.309
accused him of doping.

00:42:39.309 --> 00:42:43.069
He was wearing the yellow jersey at the tour,
he didn't like it one bit.

00:42:43.069 --> 00:42:44.819
But I was right and he was wrong you know.

00:42:44.819 --> 00:42:48.089
And he's, it doesn't always happen, you gotta
be pretty sure of your ground.

00:42:48.089 --> 00:42:50.980
It happened with Rasmussen, albeit he never
failed a dope test.

00:42:50.980 --> 00:43:15.969
Sorry can I just come to this guy?
&gt;&gt;male 7: do you think the relevance [Inaudible]

00:43:15.969 --> 00:43:21.519
over the past few years [inaudible]
&gt;&gt;Ned: Yeah.

00:43:21.519 --> 00:43:22.519
Doesn't look good.

00:43:22.519 --> 00:43:23.519
&gt;&gt;male 7: Do you think that's something that
we seize upon?

00:43:23.519 --> 00:43:24.519
Is it fair to seize upon that [Inaudible].

00:43:24.519 --> 00:43:27.470
Is it something that it's just you do something
that doesn't say you're one or the other?

00:43:27.470 --> 00:43:28.470
&gt;&gt;Richard: I think it's dangerous to make
any assumptions isn't it?

00:43:28.470 --> 00:43:29.470
I mean we could make the same assumption about
Chris Froome who rode into second in the Vuelta

00:43:29.470 --> 00:43:30.470
last year.

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:34.119
But we knew that he'd been ill and that you
had this terrible bad luck.

00:43:34.119 --> 00:43:38.809
So, it's like a very British mindset perhaps.

00:43:38.809 --> 00:43:43.039
You know the cheating foreigners and the plucky
Brit.

00:43:43.039 --> 00:43:47.769
So you know, I think it's always dangerous
to make assumptions one way or the other.

00:43:47.769 --> 00:43:49.400
There could be a logical explanation.

00:43:49.400 --> 00:43:55.029
I mean Joe Barr apparently had dental problems
that could explain it, who knows.

00:43:55.029 --> 00:43:58.079
Inconsistency though, or massive leap in improvements.

00:43:58.079 --> 00:44:00.359
&gt;&gt;Ned: Thomas Voeckler
&gt;&gt;Richard: It's always suspicious.

00:44:00.359 --> 00:44:01.359
&gt;&gt;Ned: Yeah.

00:44:01.359 --> 00:44:02.569
&gt;&gt;Daniel: Tom Boland.

00:44:02.569 --> 00:44:09.789
&gt;&gt;Richard: Well there's an interesting little
bit in your book your new book the e-book,

00:44:09.789 --> 00:44:13.130
where you have a conversation with an ESO
official who suggests that.

00:44:13.130 --> 00:44:18.089
&gt;&gt;Ned: I mean on last year's tour there at
this funny moment where it almost became a

00:44:18.089 --> 00:44:21.380
possibility that Thomas Voeckler would win
the Tour de France.

00:44:21.380 --> 00:44:26.589
I mean having been not up to consideration,
it just flickered for second, hang on this

00:44:26.589 --> 00:44:28.160
ain't gonna happen is it?

00:44:28.160 --> 00:44:33.349
But after 10 days in the yellow at which point
I said this guy who is very high up in the

00:44:33.349 --> 00:44:34.829
organization, I said.

00:44:34.829 --> 00:44:36.799
&gt;&gt;Richard: What's his name?

00:44:36.799 --> 00:44:38.279
&gt;&gt;Ned: Matthieu Peres.

00:44:38.279 --> 00:44:42.180
And I said, "That would be a thing wouldn't
it?

00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:46.670
Out of nowhere of Frenchman after all this
time winning you know we're two days from

00:44:46.670 --> 00:44:47.710
Paris.

00:44:47.710 --> 00:44:48.969
This could happen."

00:44:48.969 --> 00:44:53.289
And he went, "I hope it doesn't happen.

00:44:53.289 --> 00:44:54.400
This needs to stop now."

00:44:54.400 --> 00:44:55.400
And I went, "No!?", and he goes.

00:44:55.400 --> 00:45:01.660
[laughter]
Now I don't know, he's not party to information.

00:45:01.660 --> 00:45:03.140
But he sensitive to those insinuations.

00:45:03.140 --> 00:45:04.829
And to the image of the tour.

00:45:04.829 --> 00:45:05.829
&gt;&gt;Richard: Yeah.

00:45:05.829 --> 00:45:07.690
&gt;&gt;Daniel: This is on YouTube Ned, you know
that right.

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:09.150
&gt;&gt;Ned: Yeah.

00:45:09.150 --> 00:45:16.550
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Richard: Bleep that bit out.

00:45:16.550 --> 00:45:31.610
&gt;&gt;male 8: [Inaudible]
&gt;&gt;Richard: More time to think, I think.

00:45:31.610 --> 00:45:36.269
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I think that cycling in sports that's
least vulnerable to that kind of thing.

00:45:36.269 --> 00:45:40.489
Because I think the sport where you feel that
most is probably something like golf where

00:45:40.489 --> 00:45:41.489
you're stationary.

00:45:41.489 --> 00:45:43.080
Because no seriously.

00:45:43.080 --> 00:45:46.470
[laughter]
No because it's also it's a physiological

00:45:46.470 --> 00:45:48.660
thing, it's a hormonal thing.

00:45:48.660 --> 00:45:55.380
If you're moving, if you're moving fast your
producing hormones which will ultimately often

00:45:55.380 --> 00:45:58.410
they will kind of muffle the stress.

00:45:58.410 --> 00:46:04.069
You know like that adrenaline that works against
stress a lot of the time without becoming

00:46:04.069 --> 00:46:05.069
more nervous.

00:46:05.069 --> 00:46:07.329
I think generally – –
&gt;&gt;Richard: It's a sport Daniel.

00:46:07.329 --> 00:46:12.690
&gt;&gt;Daniel: I, but yeah outside of when they're
actually performing.

00:46:12.690 --> 00:46:14.559
Yeah I think all sportsmen are susceptible.

00:46:14.559 --> 00:46:21.640
&gt;&gt;Richard: I think the self-doubt thing, it
can be the difference between you know you

00:46:21.640 --> 00:46:27.099
start with Ullrich and Armstrong's, or any,
LeMond Hinault.

00:46:27.099 --> 00:46:30.150
Any rivalry where that's really exposed.

00:46:30.150 --> 00:46:31.940
Often the difference is confidence, self-confidence.

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:35.170
&gt;&gt;Ned: And actually there's a really good
case in point just the other week wasn't there

00:46:35.170 --> 00:46:36.170
with Johnny Hoogerland.

00:46:36.170 --> 00:46:38.369
I don't know how closely you been following
this season.

00:46:38.369 --> 00:46:42.849
But he's a kind of marauding, he doesn't quite
know what he is kind of rider, but he's got

00:46:42.849 --> 00:46:44.969
bundles of aggression and a lot of talent.

00:46:44.969 --> 00:46:49.339
And in Milan-San Ramo he kept attacking and
in slightly inappropriate places and having

00:46:49.339 --> 00:46:50.339
a go.

00:46:50.339 --> 00:46:55.150
And actually, his DS came out and said he's
doing that because his self-confidence is

00:46:55.150 --> 00:46:56.150
brittle.

00:46:56.150 --> 00:46:57.690
Cause he doesn't know how to get the best
out of himself.

00:46:57.690 --> 00:46:58.700
&gt;&gt;Richard: It's ironic isn't it.

00:46:58.700 --> 00:47:01.039
We can see, I think the with Pantani as well.

00:47:01.039 --> 00:47:05.559
Some of these great you know really excited
climbers are often the ones who are most wracked

00:47:05.559 --> 00:47:06.559
by self-doubt.

00:47:06.559 --> 00:47:10.569
And they're not happy unless they are you
know.

00:47:10.569 --> 00:47:13.499
If they're sitting in the bunch waiting for
things to happen they are not happy.

00:47:13.499 --> 00:47:18.529
And it takes a very confident rider to actually
just sit there and control it.

00:47:18.529 --> 00:47:22.999
And someone like Armstrong who would say this
was the key moment of the race, this is where

00:47:22.999 --> 00:47:24.099
I'm gonna set it alight.

00:47:24.099 --> 00:47:25.099
And do that.

00:47:25.099 --> 00:47:28.160
&gt;&gt;Daniel: But it's interesting that some people
can turn that into fuel and other people,

00:47:28.160 --> 00:47:30.319
for other people it would just kill their
performances.

00:47:30.319 --> 00:47:35.390
I mean that was, for Merckx, he was just as
wracked with self-doubt as any rider you will

00:47:35.390 --> 00:47:36.390
ever find.

00:47:36.390 --> 00:47:40.140
&gt;&gt;Richard: The nature of cycling, particularly
with the hours of training and racing, it

00:47:40.140 --> 00:47:43.790
does, if you're an introspective sort it's
gonna make you worse.

00:47:43.790 --> 00:47:45.690
I think climbing is the same.

00:47:45.690 --> 00:47:49.190
I think that's why there's some really good,
not these ones obviously, but there are some

00:47:49.190 --> 00:47:51.219
really good books out about cycling.

00:47:51.219 --> 00:47:56.210
Because there is that time to think and like
there's great climbing literature as well.

00:47:56.210 --> 00:48:01.059
Because people have this time to think and
to you know David Miller book for example

00:48:01.059 --> 00:48:04.339
is a product of you know years of introspection.

00:48:04.339 --> 00:48:10.279
And he's intelligent enough to turn that introspection
into this coherent story.

00:48:10.279 --> 00:48:14.809
And that I think is a fact of the sport definitely
significant.

00:48:14.809 --> 00:48:19.039
&gt;.Ned: And the psychological fuel thing, you
said using it as a fuel.

00:48:19.039 --> 00:48:24.079
Just to quote Gary Imlach who presents our
coverage, who's I think a brilliant brilliant

00:48:24.079 --> 00:48:25.079
journalist.

00:48:25.079 --> 00:48:28.049
He once summed up Lance Armstrong at the end
of one of our shows after he had that spat

00:48:28.049 --> 00:48:30.509
with Simeoni in the best way possible.

00:48:30.509 --> 00:48:35.989
He said, "Lance Armstrong needs grudges like
the flying Scotsman needs a steady supply

00:48:35.989 --> 00:48:36.989
of coal."

00:48:36.989 --> 00:48:39.609
[laughter]
Which I thought was just brilliant.

